Cic. ends with a strony appeal to the sympathy of the iudices to aequit those who have sacrificed so much for the state, and to whose zeal on his behalf he owes his own restoration. It is entirely because of the support they yave him that they are placed in their present unenviable position, and, if they should be convicted, he would rather share their fate and 90 into exile, than remain at Rome without them. Their acquittal will serve to confirm and strenythen the hands of the friends os law and order, while it will curb and restrain the disaffected.
